          <para styleclass="Normal"><line style="height:1px; color:#993300;" /></para>
          <para styleclass="Interface2"><text styleclass="Interface2" translate="true">Application Notes</text><text styleclass="Heading4 Toggle_atocs_" translate="true">:</text></para>
          <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><table styleclass="Block" rowcount="1" colcount="1">
            <tr style="vertical-align:top">
              <td>
                <para styleclass="VariableName"><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">Dynamic Performance</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">The </text><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">Cycloidal CV50 Motion-Law</text><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true"> is recommended in applications where you need the peak velocity to be low when compared to others. It has a large Peak Acceleration, with a short duration, thus more likely to induce vibrations.</text></para>
                <para styleclass="VariableName"><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">Pressure Angle Considerations</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">It gives a relatively low pressure angle - because of its low peak velocity.</text></para>
                <para styleclass="VariableName"><text styleclass="VariableName" translate="true">Drive Torques</text></para>
                <para styleclass="Body Text HowTo"><text styleclass="Body Text HowTo" translate="true">This Motion-Law is not recommended in many applications as it gives a sudden change in torque. The input transmission rigidity would need to be high.</text></para>
              </td>
            </tr>
          </table></para>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table></para>
